description:
Soil is the foundation of gardening. A healthy, well balanced soil is key to having a productive garden. The soil delivers water and nutrients to crops, physically supports plants, and helps control pests. Fertile soil results when minerals, organic matter, air and water are plentiful and balanced and is determined by the ability of the soil to provide all the essential nutrients in an available form. Majority of soil life is found in the top few inches of soil since micro-organisms are not able to survive six inches below because there is not sufficient oxygen. 
In soil management, mild tilling will allow air to be able to penetrate deep in the soil thus increasing the ability of micro-organisms to thrive further beneath the surface. However, allow the soil micro-organism to remain undisturbed wherever possible. The primary goal of soil management is to protect soil and enhance its performance, so gardening can be profitable. Optimum production is achieved by adding minerals and compost each growing season so that plants can be more flavorful, pests and disease resistant and nutritious.
Macro-nutrients such as nitrogen, hydrogen, oxygen, phosphorus, carbon, potassium and calcium are some of the elements needed in good quantity. Micronutrients are only needed in small amounts and these include iron, zinc, magnesium, sulphur, copper, etc. If these nutrients are not adequately supplied, then plant deficiencies may show externally until nutrients are corrected before damage is beyond repair. Nutrient deficiencies may result in pests and disease on plants. Since plants are using nutrients in soil to convert inorganic matter to organic food, these nutrients need to be replaced by adding humus, organic matter or organic fertilizers. Unless this is done, plants will not be as healthy or balanced and will not provide the vitamins and minerals our bodies need to be in health.
